README.md
     4‚Üí## Note
     5‚Üí
     6‚Üí-   Sections are treated as nested objects.
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí-   Section-less items are treated as globals.
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí## Usage
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíConsider an INI file such as the following:
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí```ini
    15‚Üí; This comment is being ignored
    16‚Üíscope = global
    17‚Üí
    18‚Üí[database]
    19‚Üíuser = dbuser
    20‚Üípassword = dbpassword
    21‚Üídatabase = use_this_database
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí[paths.default]
    24‚Üídatadir = /var/lib/data
    25‚Üíarray[] = first value
    26‚Üíarray[] = second value
    27‚Üíarray[] = third value
    28‚Üí```
    29‚Üí
    30‚ÜíYou can **read**, **modify** and **write** it like so:
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    82‚Üí## API
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üí### Parse
    85‚Üí
    86‚ÜíAttempts to turn the given INI string into a nested data object.
    87‚Üí
    88‚Üí```js
    89‚Üí// You can also use `decode`
    90‚Üíconst object = parse(`<INI Text>`) 
    91‚Üí```
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí### Stringify
    94‚Üí
    95‚ÜíEncodes the given data object as an INI formatted string.
    96‚Üí
    97‚Üí```js
    98‚Üí// You can also use `encode`
    99‚Üístringify(object,{
   100‚Üí
   101‚Üí    /**
   102‚Üí     *  Whether to insert spaces before & after `=`
   103‚Üí     * 
   104‚Üí     *  Disabled by default to have better 
   105‚Üí     *  compatibility with old picky parsers.
   106‚Üí     */
   107‚Üí
   108‚Üí    whitespace : false ,
   109‚Üí
   110‚Üí    /**
   111‚Üí     *  Whether to align the `=` character for each section.
   112‚Üí     *  -> Also enables the `whitespace` option
   113‚Üí     */
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   167‚Üí### Un / Escape
   168‚Üí
   169‚ÜíTurn the given string into a safe to  
   170‚Üíuse key or value in your INI file.
   171‚Üí
   172‚Üí```js
   173‚Üísafe(`"unsafe string"`) // -> \"unsafe string\"
   174‚Üí```
   175‚Üí
   176‚ÜíOr reverse the process with:
   177‚Üí
   178‚Üí```js
   179‚Üíunsafe(`\\"safe string\\"`) // -> "safe string"
   180‚Üí```
